In the ſixth Year of Juſtine the Great, Edeſſa, that Noble and Bleſſed City of the Oſroenians, was over flown with the Streams of the River Scirtus, that glided by i; inſomuch as many Houſes were carried away with the violence thereof, and multitudes of Men were drowned with the Water: [See Evagrius's Eccleſiaſtical Hiſtory, lib. 4. chap. 8.] And Cedrenus reports, That at the ſame time, in the Bank of the River, a Table of Stone was found, whereon was Written in Egyptian Letters to this effect;



                     Scirtus the Stream ſhall Leap and Dance,

And cauſe Edeſſas great miſchance.

